[{"id":"page_0193-b001","page_key":193,"order":1,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"b)"},{"id":"page_0193-b002","page_key":193,"order":2,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"c)"},{"id":"page_0193-b003","page_key":193,"order":3,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"figure","image_path":"figures/page_0193_fig_1.jpg"},{"id":"page_0193-b004","page_key":193,"order":4,"type":"caption","source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","text":"Figure 11.6 Variance in residual networks. a) He initialization ensures that the expected variance remains unchanged after a linear plus ReLU layer $f_{k}$ . Unfortunately, in residual networks, the input of each bloc..."},{"id":"page_0193-b005","page_key":193,"order":5,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"equation","text":"\\begin{array}{rcl}m_{h}&=&\\frac{1}{\\left|\\mathcal{B}\\right|}\\sum\\limits_{i\\in\\mathcal{B}}h_{i}\\\\s_{h}&=&\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{\\left|\\mathcal{B}\\right|}\\sum\\limits_{i\\in\\mathcal{B}}(h_{i}-m_{h})^{2}},\\end{array} \\quad (11.7)"},{"id":"page_0193-b006","page_key":193,"order":6,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"where all quantities are scalars. Then we use these statistics to standardize the batch activations to have mean zero and unit variance:"},{"id":"page_0193-b007","page_key":193,"order":7,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"equation","text":"s_{h}\\quad=\\quad\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{\\left|\\mathcal{B}\\right|}\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{B}}(h_{i}-m_{h})^{2}}, \\quad (11.7)"},{"id":"page_0193-b008","page_key":193,"order":8,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"where $\\epsilon$ is a small number that prevents division by zero if $h_{i}$ is the same for every member of the batch and $s_{h}=0$."},{"id":"page_0193-b009","page_key":193,"order":9,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"Finally, the normalized variable is scaled by $\\gamma$ and shifted by $\\delta$:"},{"id":"page_0193-b010","page_key":193,"order":10,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"equation","text":"h_{i}\\leftarrow\\gamma h_{i}+\\delta\\qquad\\quad\\forall i\\in\\mathcal{B}. \\quad (11.9)"},{"id":"page_0193-b011","page_key":193,"order":11,"source":"deepseek+paddle","confidence":"medium","type":"paragraph","text":"Draft: please send errata to udlbookmail@gmail.com."}]
